	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>HAND OF THE HAMMERS, PART I</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><p>The winds howled in frozen fury, blowing ice and snow with a numbing berserker rage. Still the barbarians trekked onward, clutching their furs close and bending heads to duck the gale. “Why could you not have sent your apprentice?” Eban shouted, leaning next to his wife’s ear. “This is no time for you to be traveling.”</p>

<p>Freyda shook her head. “You know he’ll not see any healer but me, and he’s too sick to come to Halas himself,” she replied. “I couldn’t leave him out on the tundra to die, Eban.”</p>

<p>“You’re nine moons with child, Freyda! Going out in the teeth of a blizzard is foolhardy, even for a healer. And don’t you give me that look, I don’t care of your healer’s duty when our child is at risk.” He scowled. “I should never have let you talk me into this.”</p>

<p>“You had little choice, husband. If you had not agreed, I would have simply gone myself.” She grinned up at him from beneath her bearskin hat. “You worry too much. I will be just fine, you’ll see. Are you sure we’re going the right way?” Squinting, she looked into the blowing snow. “I can hardly see my hand in front of my face.”</p>

<p>“And now who worries too much? I know my way home, even through the storm. We go this way, straight on, and we will come to…Freyda?” She had stopped dead in her tracks, doubled over at the waist and arms wrapped about her belly. His brow knotted in concern. “Freyda? What is it?”</p>

<p>Sweat froze into a thin sheen of ice on her face as she looked up at him. “How close are we?”</p>

<p>He shook his head. “Not close. We still have miles of tundra to cross.”</p>

<p>“Then find us a place to stop, Eban, please?” Her deep eyes filled with pain and worry. “The child is coming, and I do not think I can make it back before it is born.”</p>

<p>The warrior thought quickly, scanning the frozen wastes for any shelter. After a moment he lifted her in his large arms, carrying her against his chest even through the worst of the gale. At last he ducked into the ruins of an ancient building, tumbling down but still sturdy enough to withstand any ravages but those of time.</p>

<p>Setting her gently on her feet, he pulled three pelts from his pack and laid them on the floor. He placed a fourth nearby, then set his pack against the wall and steadied her as she eased onto the makeshift bed. Already her face was furrowed with birthing pains. “So suddenly? Our sons took so much longer.”</p>

<p>“Children…come as they will….” Her voice broke, and she took a deep breath. “Once a warrior…now a midwife. The…birthing of this child…will be yours, Eban.”</p>

<p>He had seen seasons of combat, had stood strong before orcish hoardes and stampeding mammoths. But he would rather stand against a legion of ice giants than the duty that faced him now. Shoving fear aside, he knelt on the cold stone floor.</p>

<p>What ensued has been described in countless tales before. But in the end, Eban held a tiny child, dark hair a fuzz upon a small head and eyes as deep as the night that had fallen. With a tenderness surprising in a battle-hardened warrior, he swaddled his little one tightly in a soft bear pelt and carried her into the blizzard.</p>

<p>In strong hands he held her high for all the world and gods to see. “Hammers, look you down and see my child! The day of her birth has been written in the earth and stones, and sung upon the wind. Write you now the day of her final breath, and may it be far in the future, that she may serve the cause of Justice for decades yet to come.”</p>

<p>Snow swirled about him, caressing the tiny form he cradled. Finally he returned to the shelter and placed the little bundle in his wife’s arms. Through her exhaustion she smiled up at him. “What shall we call her?” she asked, pulling back the furs to look at the delicate face.</p>

<p>He tilted his head and looked at her. Reaching down, he stroked one soft cheek, then ruffled the white fur that held her. “I think…we shall call her Ursi.”</p>
 </font></td>
	</tr>
